          <p>
            The cornerstone lens for Z6 III users. Razor-sharp across the entire
            frame, fast and silent autofocus, and professional build quality. The
            best general-purpose zoom for weddings, events, and travel.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Nikon Z 70-200mm f/2.8 VR S</h4>
          <p>
            Flagship telephoto with outstanding optics and image stabilization.
            Combined with the Z6 III's IBIS, you can handhold at remarkably slow
            shutter speeds. Perfect for sports, wildlife, and portrait work.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Nikon Z 35mm f/1.8 S</h4>
          <p>
            A compact, affordable prime that punches above its weight. Extremely
            sharp, beautiful bokeh, and weather-sealed. Ideal for street
            photography, environmental portraits, and low-light shooting.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Nikon Z 50mm f/1.2 S</h4>
          <p>
            Nikon's flagship normal lens delivers stunning image quality and
            ultra-smooth bokeh. While expensive and hefty, it's unmatched for
            portrait work and creates images with a unique rendering.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="section faq-section">
      <h2 class="section-title">Nikon Z6 III FAQ</h2>

      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">
            How does the Z6 III compare to the Sony A7 IV?
            <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              The Z6 III offers better video specs (6K vs 4K 60p), superior
              ergonomics, and longer battery life. The A7 IV counters with higher
              resolution (33MP vs 24MP) and wider native lens selection. Both have
              excellent autofocus, but Nikon's latest system is slightly more
              reliable in challenging conditions. Choose Z6 III for video-centric
              work, A7 IV if you need maximum resolution.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">
            Is the Z6 III good for wildlife photography?
            <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Yes, very good but with caveats. The improved autofocus with bird
              detection is excellent, and 14fps is adequate for most situations.
              However, the 24MP resolution limits extreme cropping compared to
              higher-res cameras. It's ideal for wildlife video (4K 120p, 6K),
              and the buffer can handle long bursts. For resolution-critical work,
              consider the Z8.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">
            What memory cards work best with the Z6 III?
            <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              For 6K N-RAW recording, you'll need CFexpress Type B cards with
              minimum 1400MB/s write speed (recommended: Sony TOUGH or ProGrade
              Cobalt). For 4K video and photography, high-speed UHS-II SD cards
              (V90 rated) work excellently. The dual-slot design allows CFexpress
              for video and SD for photo backup, optimizing workflow.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">
            Does the Z6 III overheat during extended video recording?
            <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Heat management is excellent. In standard temperature mode, 4K 60p
              can record for 125+ minutes continuously. Even 6K N-RAW recording
              is possible for 40-50 minutes before thermal limits. The camera
              includes High Temperature settings that extend recording time further,
              though with slightly increased fan noise. Overheating is not a
              practical concern for most users.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">
            Who should buy the Nikon Z6 III?
            <span class="faq-toggle">+</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              The Z6 III is ideal for hybrid shooters who value ergonomics, video
              features, and reliable performance. It's perfect for wedding
              photographers, documentary filmmakers, event coverage, and content
              creators who need both excellent stills and professional video.
              Skip it if you primarily shoot stills and need maximum resolutionâ€”
              consider the Z8 instead.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Recommendation -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="final-verdict">
        <h2>Final Recommendation</h2>
        <p>
          The Nikon Z6 III is the hybrid camera Nikon users have been requesting.
          It doesn't chase specifications for spec sheet superiorityâ€”instead,
          it delivers practical, usable features that make real-world shooting
          easier and more productive. The combination of excellent image quality,
          professional video capabilities, and refined ergonomics creates a tool
          you'll rely on day after day.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Buy it if:</strong> You're a hybrid shooter who values video
          quality, ergonomics, and reliability. Perfect for weddings, events,
          documentary work, and content creation.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Skip it if:</strong> You primarily shoot stills and need maximum
          resolution for extensive croppingâ€”the Z8 or Z9 are better choices.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
